results.notes:
Habitat: On shale (or at least shale-like sedimentary rock) along Figueroa Mountain Road at Ranger Peak west-facing slope in Pseudotsuga macrocarpa forest.

Macro: Thallus light grayish-brownish-yellow, black prothallus, black apothecia up to 0.5 mm diam., white medulla, photobiont green, apothecia immersed, lecanorine or cryptolecanorine

Micro: proper exciple not obvious, epihymenium brown, hymenium hyaline, subhymenium very light brown, almost hyaline though. Paraphyses appear to widen toward tips.

Spores: ovoid, 1-septate, gray to brown (brown ones seemed overmature), constricted at septation, measured 4: 13.4 × 8.9, 15.3 × 8.5, 15.4 × 9.2, 15.9 × 8.9 um. After spore clearing using lighter method, spores didn’t reveal much difference from pre-clearing. Walls fairly uniformly thin.

Thallus: K+ yellow

*Note: no idea what genus this is. Brodo 2016 key takes me to Rinodina, which I don’t think it is, but really just not sure.

results.notes:
I live in the Pacific Northwest, specifically on Camano Island in Island County, WA.

We moved into this house last April. Recently with cooler weather and rains we’ve had an “explosion” of mushrooms in the grass of the yard. This yard was hydro-seeded before we moved in by former owner.

With so many mushrooms (in quantity not species) I got curious as to what I’m seeing. I’m a botanist but never delved into fungi. So I have a fairly decent biological background. I’m also a keen native plants and animals photographer.

OK enough of that! But I thought it might help you all in helping me ID. I took these photos this afternoon (October 10th)These are pure white. It’s really a beautiful pure white when freshly mature. This is the most common mushroom in my yard at present. Thanks for any help.

DNA Sequencing Results & Discussion (posted on 20-May-21; updated on 5-Jul-22):
A full-length nrITS sequence of 618 base pairs (bps) was obtained by Dr. Kudzma from this collection and posted to this observation. It was derived entirely from the reverse read that required manual resolution of two haplotypes due to a single point of heterogeneity in the early ITS1 region. The forward read would have been essential in simplifying the task of assembling a joined contig in this scenario, had it not suffered from substantial noise in early ITS1 up to the point of heterogeneity, rendering it essentially useless. The haplotypes are present in ~1.2:1 ratio (area under the curve), favoring the shorter one that has TT vs. the one with the extra T. The ITS sequence is bookended on the 5’ end by the last 46 characters of nrSSU and by the first 24 characters of nrLSU on the 3’ end. A single ambiguity, “M” (A/C), is seen in the ITS1 sublocus in the reverse read. This, however, gets resolved in the forward read due to the 1-base frame shift; the major/shorter haplotype has a “C” there.
The ITS sequence is 99.68% identical to that of Tricholoma columbetta neotype, LT000017. The two mismatching positions involve ambiguities (R, R) in the holotype sequence. Judging from the abundance of highly similar hits in GenBank (98.6-100% identity), this European taxon is common and widespread in North America.

results.notes:
These photos are provided by the owner who lost her dog on October 3 of this year after eating a similar mushroom. I don’t yet know what type of dog it is, but our club has taken the identification of this mushroom on as a project. Not all photos sent by owner are included here. Below is the owners description. There is no mention of odor. Microscopy of spores by me.
Caps: Tan/light brown, bell shaped with a dark brown conical bump in the center, and appear to have fibers. Caps on the older specimens are split. Cap widths on 2 specimens collected ranged 2-3.5 cm
Stalk: Brown at base, white for rest of length. Length of 2 specimens collected ranged 3.4- 4.5 cm
Gills: attached and off white in color when fresh, grayish brown on specimens several hours/days after collection.
Spore print: brown.
Habitat: Growing from the ground in a shady lawn. Lawn is mostly weeds (stilt grass, Indian strawberry, trefoil and smartweed) in fruiting area. Trees present include oak trees (mostly white oak, a few red oak), maples and tulip trees.
See photo for view of fruiting area:
The mushrooms appeared in the lawn in the area bounded in the front by the 2 white oaks (photo foreground), split rail fence on the left side and holly hedge on the right side of photo.
Note: there is another white oak tree that isn’t in view—it’s hidden by the bushes to the right roughly where the red oak tree stump is located (stump is visible in the photo).
At the time my dog became sick, the mushrooms were fruiting in front of the left white oak tree between the lilac bush (in center of photo several feet in front of the red oak tree stump) and the split rail fence.
What species?
